# Introduction

## What is Version Control?

Version Control is a system that records changes made to files over time. It allows you to track every modification, restore previous versions if needed, and collaborate with other developers without losing work.

Instead of creating multiple copies of the same project (such as `project_final`, `project_final_v2`, or `project_latest`), a Version Control System (VCS) keeps the complete history of changes in an organized manner.

---

## Why Do We Need Version Control?

Imagine you are building a website.

On Monday, you create the homepage.

On Tuesday, you add a login page.

On Wednesday, you accidentally delete an important file.

Without Version Control, recovering that deleted file can be difficult or even impossible.

With Version Control, you can easily restore your project to a previous working version.

Version Control helps developers:

- Track every change made to a project.
- Restore previous versions.
- Work safely without fear of losing code.
- Collaborate with multiple developers.
- Maintain a complete history of the project.

---

## Real-Life Example

Imagine you are writing a college assignment.

You save it with names like:

```
Assignment.docx
Assignment_Final.docx
Assignment_Final2.docx
Assignment_Final_Last.docx
Assignment_ReallyFinal.docx
```

After a few days, you don't know which file is the latest.

Version Control solves this problem by automatically maintaining every version in one place, along with information about what changed and when it changed.

---

## What is Git?

Git is a **Distributed Version Control System (DVCS)** used to track changes in source code and other files.

It allows developers to:

- Save project history.
- Track changes.
- Restore previous versions.
- Work offline.
- Collaborate with teams.
- Merge changes from different developers.

Git was created by **Linus Torvalds** in **2005** to help manage the development of the Linux kernel.

Today, Git is the most widely used Version Control System in software development.

---

## What is GitHub?

GitHub is a cloud-based platform that hosts Git repositories.

While Git works on your local computer, GitHub stores your repositories online, making it easier to back up projects, collaborate with others, and share your work.

GitHub provides additional features such as:

- Repository hosting
- Collaboration
- Pull Requests
- Issues
- Project management
- GitHub Actions
- GitHub Pages

Think of Git as the engine that manages your project history, and GitHub as the online platform where you store and share your Git repositories.

---

## Git vs GitHub

| Git | GitHub |
|------|---------|
| A Version Control System | A cloud-based hosting platform |
| Installed on your computer | Accessible through a web browser |
| Tracks file changes | Stores Git repositories online |
| Can work completely offline | Requires the internet for most collaboration features |
| Used to manage project history | Used to collaborate and share projects |

---

